RONALD CLARKE GREW UP IN NYC.
THE NYPL SYSTEM ALLOWED EMPLOYEES TO LIVE IN THE BUILDINGS.
HIS FATHER GOT A JOB AS A CUSTODIAN OF ONE OF THE LIBRARIES.
EVEN THE TOPS OF THE BOOKCASES WERE WAXED!
HIS FATHER TOOK A LOT OF PRIDE IN HIS WORK.
RONALD WAS RELUCTANT TO TELL OTHER CHILDREN WHERE HE LIVED.
THE LIBRARY HAD SOME STRANGE THINGS FOR A HOME.
HE HAD TO BE QUIET ALL DAY, BUT COULD RUN AND PLAY AFTER THE LIBRARY CLOSED FOR THE DAY.
HE WOULD OFTEN THINK OF A QUESTION LATE AT NIGHT AND RUN DOWN TO THE STACKS TO FIND A BOOK FOR AN ANSWER.
RONALD WAS THE FIRST IN HIS FAMILY TO GO TO COLLEGE, AND BECAME A PROFESSOR WHEN HE GRADUATED.
HE TOOK HIS DAD TO SEE HIS CLASSROOM, WHICH WAS EMBLAZONED WITH PROFESSOR CLARKE ON THE DOOR.
HIS FATHER WAS QUIET, BUT RONALD KNEW FROM THE LOOK HIS FATHER GAVE HIM THAT HIS FATHER WAS VERY PROUD.
RONALD IS THANKFUL FOR THE LIBRARY, AND DOESN'T KNOW HOW HIS LIFE WOULD HAVE BEEN WITHOUT IT.
RONALD CLARKE GREW UP POOR IN NYC.
HIS FATHER GOT A JOB AS A CUSTODIAN AT AN NYPL LOCATION.
HIS FATHER TOOK A LOT OF PRIDE IN HIS JOB.
HIS FATHER CLEANED EVERYTHING SO IT SINED.
HE EVEN WAXED THE TOPS OF BOOKSHELVES.
HIS FAMILY MOVED INTO THE LIBRARY, BECAUSE THE NYPL LET EMPLOYEES LIVE THERE IN THE 40'S.
RONALD NEVER HAD FRIENDS OVER BECAUSE HE WAS EMBARRASSED ABOUT LIVING IN A DIFFERENT SPACE THAN OTHER KIDS.
RONALD HAD TO BE QUIET AND PLAY QUIETLY DURING THE DAY, BUT COULD RUN THROUGHOUT THE LIBRARY ONCE IT CLOSED FOR THE DAY.
HE WOULD OFTEN WANT TO KNOW SOMETHING, GO TO THE STACKS TO LOOK IT UP, AND STAY UP READING UNTIL 3AM.
NO ONE IN HIS FAMILY HAD A DEGREE.
HE WENT ON TO GRADUATE SCHOOL, AND BECAME A PROFESSOR.
RONALD TOOK HIS FATHER TO SEE HIS CLASSROOM ONE DAY.
HIS FATHER WAS VERY QUIET, BUT GAVE HIM A PROUD LOOK.
RONALD DOESN'T KNOW HOW HIS LIFE WOULD HAVE BEEN WITHOUT GROWING UP IN THE LIBRARY.
